{"type":"message","id":"371e0aa4","parentId":"ed5a3280","timestamp":"2026-03-15T00:39:01.914Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"It seems the process tool requires a sessionId for most actions. Let me try a different approach - I'll use the read tool to explore the directory. But first, let me try to understand the structure by reading files directly.\n\nActually, I should try to list the directory contents. Let me check if there's a way to do this. The process tool seems to need a sessionId. Let me try running an exec session differently.\n\nWait, looking at the process tool description again, it says \"Manage running exec sessions: list, poll, log, write, send-keys, submit, paste, kill.\" The exec action might not be available directly. Let me try using read to explore the directory structure.\n\nActually, I can try reading a file path that might exist. Let me first try to read the directory by attempting to read files. But that's inefficient.\n\nLet me try a different approach - I'll use the process tool with exec action but I need to understand how sessions work. Looking at the output, it seems sessions need to be created first. Let me check if there's another way.\n\nActually, I realize I should just try to read files in that directory. Let me start by trying to list what's there using PowerShell commands through process. But I need a sessionId first.\n\nLet me try to create a session by using process with some action that creates one. Looking at the actions available: list, poll, log, write, send-keys, submit, paste, kill. None of these seem to create a session directly.\n\nWait, I think I need to use the process tool differently. Let me try using it with action that would start a session. Perhaps I need to use a different approach entirely.\n\nActually, the simplest approach might be to just try reading files in the docs directory using the read tool. Let me try reading common documentation files that might exist there.",